# Writeup 2 - Injection payload
- Christian Jay Siton

This time, I attempted a PicoCTF for web exploiting called Local Authority. The challenge gave me a website that led me to a login page.
Login pages typically require you to input a username and password, which is commonly exploited with an injection payload.
I learned injection payloads exploits the vulnerability of input checks of a website.

An injection payload I learned looks something like this:
username/password: " or ""="

This works because in systems like SQL queries it would look something like this:
* SELECT * FROM Users WHERE Name ="" or ""="" AND Pass ="" or ""=""
which would always return true.

Although the website did some checks to validate inputs to some extent, it was not enough as we able to intercept
and see the script responsible for the username and password, worse it contained the actual values for those fields.
Using the actual username and password required by the website contained in those scripts, I successfully
logged in and obtained the flag.

